    "questionText": "A cable tray section rises at an angle of 30° from the horizontal. The horizontal distance (Adjacent side) of this rise is 15 metres. \n\n1) Using the Cosine ratio (Cos θ = Adjacent / Hypotenuse), transpose the formula to find the length of the diagonal tray (Hypotenuse) and calculate the result to two decimal places. \n\n2) The circuit is supplied at 400V. The maximum permitted voltage drop for this installation is 3%. Calculate the maximum allowable voltage drop in Volts.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Diagonal Tray Length: 17.32 metres (Calculated as Hypotenuse = 15 / Cos 30°).",
      "Maximum Voltage Drop: 12V (Calculated as 400V × 0.03 or [400 / 100] × 3)."
    ],
    "hint": "For the first part, remember 'change the side, change the sign'—to get the Hypotenuse on its own, you'll need to swap its position with the Cosine value. For the second part, 3% is the same as 3 per 100."
